[`memcpy`](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/string/byte/memcpy) should be used for that:
```
#include &lt;iostream&gt;
#include &lt;string&gt;
#include &lt;cstring&gt;
#include &lt;cassert&gt;

int main() {
    char const s[] = &quot;HERE&quot;;
    int i;
    std::memcpy(&amp;i, s, sizeof i);
    std::cout &lt;&lt; i &lt;&lt; &#39;\n&#39;;

    std::string s2 = &quot;HERE&quot;;
    assert(s2.length() &gt;= sizeof i);
    std::memcpy(&amp;i, s2.data(), sizeof i);
    std::cout &lt;&lt; i &lt;&lt; &#39;\n&#39;;

    // Copy back to char[] array.
    char s3[sizeof i + 1] = {}; // +1 byte for 0 terminator and 0-initialize.
    std::memcpy(s3, &amp;i, sizeof i);
    std::cout &lt;&lt; s &lt;&lt; &#39;\n&#39;;
}
```

It does output `1163019592` on a little-endian x86 platform. On a big-endian platform the bytes of the integer are reversed. In other words, the output is implementation-defined.

Decimal `1163019592` is binary `01000101 01010010 01000101 01001000`, which is hex `0x45 0x52 0x45 0x48`.

`&quot;HERE&quot;` is bytes `0x48 0x45 0x52 0x45`.

Same bytes, different order.

If you want `&quot;HERE&quot;` to equate to `1163019592` without regard to endian, try this:

```c++
int main()
{
    string s = &quot;HERE&quot;;
    size_t n = s.length();

    uint32_t number = 0;

    for (int i = 0; i &lt; n; i++) {
        number = (number &lt;&lt; 8) | static_cast&lt;uint8_t&gt;(s[n-i-1]);
    }

    cout &lt;&lt; number;
}
```

[Live demo](https://ideone.com/HbbX8g)

